# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-liberation-organisation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] The half hour program follows the evening news, and is the flagship program for the network, with *The Sydney Morning Herald* saying "*7.30* remains arguably [the ABC's] most impactful daily program.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] From 1986 to 2011 it was called ***The 7.30 Report***; in 2011 it was rebranded as *7.30* and *Stateline* was folded into the revamped program.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] Until the end of 1995 the program had separate editions for each state and territory, presented by Alan Carpenter, Mary Delahunty, Quentin Dempster, Trisha Goddard, Sarah Henderson, Jane Singleton, Genevieve Hussey, John Jost, Leigh McClusky, Kelly Nestor, and Andrew Olle.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] Kerry O'Brien took over as the presenter of the national program on 4 December 1995, with Maxine McKew serving as the main relief presenter until 2006.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] O'Brien announced in 2010 that he would be leaving at the end of the year.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] He presented his final edition of the program on 9 December 2010.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] In February 1996, the Friday episode of the show was replaced with *Stateline*, a similar show with a separate edition for each state and territory.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] The program usually comprised several pre-recorded items and live interviews, focusing on issues of national or global significance.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] The program traditionally featured interviews with politicians.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] Paul Lyneham also hosted *The 7.30 Report* for several years.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] Until 2010, satirists John Clarke and Bryan Dawe presented a (usually) weekly mock interview covering a topical issue.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] Dawe played the interviewer, while Clarke played a prominent public figure but, unusually for satire, he deliberately made no attempt to imitate the appearance, voice, or mannerisms of the person he portrayed.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] When portraying Julia Gillard he placed a flower pot behind him to give the impression of him being a woman.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] These interviews were a continuation of the pair's work for *A Current Affair*, beginning in 1989, for which they won a number of awards.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] The ABC announced in December 2010 that the program would return in 2011 in a new form, under the name *7.30*.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] The revamped program was first presented by Leigh Sales from Sydney.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] Chris Uhlmann was *7.30'*s first political editor and Canberra presenter.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] The ABC also announced that Stateline would be folded into the *7.30* program.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] The change saw *7.30* extended to five nights a week, although Friday editions continued to be presented locally and focus on state affairs.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] The program first aired on 7 March 2011.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] In 2012, Uhlmann was appointed as *7.30* political editor, therefore stepping down as host.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] Uhlmann remained as political editor until 2013, when he announced that he would be working on a documentary about the Rudd and Gillard governments for the ABC.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] Sabra Lane replaced him as political editor, until she left to host the ABC morning radio current affairs program, *AM*.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] In 2015, Jo Puccini was appointed executive producer of the program.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] In December 2016, the ABC announced that Andrew Probyn would replace Sabra Lane as political editor.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] In August 2017, Probyn moved to a new role as the ABC's political editor replacing Chris Uhlmann who left the broadcaster for the Nine Network.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] In February 2018, Laura Tingle was appointed as political editor, replacing Probyn.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] In 2014, Sarah Ferguson hosted the show whilst Leigh Sales was on maternity leave.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] She received critical acclaim for her hard-hitting interview style from many Australian media outlets.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] In 2018, Justin Stevens was appointed executive producer.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] In February 2022, Sales announced that she would be stepping down as host, after almost 12 years in the role.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] She finished hosting the program in June, after the federal election, but continued to work for the ABC.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] In April 2022, ABC announced that Sarah Ferguson would return from her role as special correspondent in Washington, D.C. to succeed Sales as the host of *7.30* from July 2022.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] Joel Tozer was announced as the new executive producer of the program in June 2022, taking over from Justin Stevens, who was appointed director of news for the network.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] In May 2025, ABC announced that Laura Tingle would be departing *7.30* after six years to take on a new role as global affairs editor.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] Tingle was replaced by Jacob Greber, former chief digital political correspondent at the ABC.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] David Speers is currently a fill-in presenter.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] On 28 November 2014, Quentin Dempster announced the final episode of the state editions would be the following week (5 December 2014), corresponding with his departure from the public broadcaster.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] The state editions of *7.30* were broadcast on ABC at 7:30 p.m., with eight separate state and territory specific editions.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/7-30-report] Each local version of *7.30* was also broadcast nationally on ABC News over the weekend.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists disagree on the strategy that must be used to achieve their goal.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists such as Steven Best and David Nibert argue, respectively, that embracing alliance politics and militant direct action for change (including civil disobedience, mass confrontation, etc), and transcending capitalism are integral to ending animal exploitation.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists generally oppose movements that seek to make animal use more humane or to abolish specific forms of animal use, since they believe this undermines the movement to abolish all forms of animal use.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] The objective is to secure a moral and legal paradigm shift, whereby animals are no longer regarded as things to be owned and used.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] The American philosopher Tom Regan writes that abolitionists want empty cages, not bigger ones.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] This is contrasted with animal welfare, which seeks incremental reform, and animal protectionism, which seeks to combine the first principles of abolitionism with an incremental approach, but which is regarded by some abolitionists as another form of welfarism or "New Welfarism".
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] The word relates to the historical term abolitionism—a social movement to end slavery or human ownership of other humans.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Based on the way of evaluating welfare reforms, abolitionists can be either radical or pragmatic.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] While the former maintain that welfare reforms can only be dubiously described as moral improvements, the latter consider welfare reforms as moral improvements even when the conditions they permit are unjust.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] He calls such groups the "new welfarists", arguing that, though their aim is an end to animal use, the reforms they pursue are indistinguishable from reforms agreeable to traditional welfarists, who he says have no interest in abolishing animal use.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] He argues that reform campaigns entrench the property status of animals, and validate the view that animals simply need to be treated better.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Instead, he writes, the public's view that animals can be used and consumed ought to be challenged.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] His position is that this should be done by promoting ethical veganism.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Others think that this should be done by creating a public debate in society.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] He rhetorically asks, how can one hope to create some consumer base for this new vegan world when over a billion people live on less than a dollar a day?
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Nibert acknowledges that post-capitalism on its own will not automatically end animal exploitation or bring about a more just world, but that it is a "necessary precondition" for such changes.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] New welfarists argue that there is no logical or practical contradiction between abolitionism and "welfarism".
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Welfarists think that they can be working toward abolition, but by gradual steps, pragmatically taking into account what most people can be realistically persuaded to do in the short as well as the long term, and reduce animal suffering as it is most urgent to relieve.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, for example, in addition to promoting local improvements in the treatment of animals, promote vegetarianism.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Although some people believe that changing the legal status of nonhuman sentient beings is a first step in abolishing ownership or mistreatment, others argue that this will not succeed if the consuming public has not already begun to reduce or eliminate its exploitation of animals for food.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 1992, Switzerland amended its constitution to recognize animals as *beings* and not *things*.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] The dignity of animals is also protected in Switzerland.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] New Zealand granted basic rights to five great ape species in 1999.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Their use is now forbidden in research, testing or teaching.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] Germany added animal welfare in a 2002 amendment to its constitution, becoming the first European Union member to do so.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2007, the parliament of the Balearic Islands, an autonomous province of Spain, passed the world's first legislation granting legal rights to all great apes.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2013, India officially recognized dolphins as non-human persons.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2014, France revised the legal status of animals from movable property to sentient beings.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2015, the province of Quebec in Canada adopted the Animal Welfare and Safety Act, which gave animals the legal status of "sentient beings with biological needs".
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] Animal Liberation continues to oppose live export, with campaigns dating back over 30 years with original founder Christine Townend.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] In 1995, Mark Pearson and 32 others chained themselves to sow cages at Parkville piggery, part-owned by then prime minister Paul Keating.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] The result of this action was a subsequent ban on the tethering of sows.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] Animal Liberation maintains an active campaign against pig-dogging since its legal status was declared in 2006.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] In 2010, Lynda Stoner went undercover to a two-day workshop on pig-dog hunting to gather information and footage of the practice.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] Stoner has remained outspoken against all forms of hunting.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] In May 2013, Stoner compared hunting photos to images of child pornography, bestiality, snuff murders, rape and torture.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] The organisation consistently holds protests outside circuses with performing animals, such as lions and monkeys.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] One goal of this campaign is to encourage local councils to amend their policies to exclude animal circuses from public land, such as in 2013 when members of Gosford City Council put forward a motion for a ban in that area.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] In July 2013, circus campaign spokesperson Phillip Hall drew media attention to the life of captivity awaiting newborn lion cubs born into Stardust Circus.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] The escape of a performing monkey from Lennon Bros Circus in July 2014 was also heavily criticised by Animal Liberation.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] Animal Liberation has spoken out against the pet industry breeding animals for profit in puppy farms, resulting in tens of thousands of dogs and cats being euthanised per year.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] Animal Liberation has also conducted multiple undercover investigations on the conditions of animals raised for food in Australia.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] In 2001 footage received by Animal Liberation from an unknown person contained images of the stunning and slaughter of possums at Lenah Game Meats in northern Tasmania.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] This was passed onto the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) who broadcast the footage.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] Lenah Game Meats took action against ABC, with the Supreme Court of Tasmania granting an injunction against the footage being broadcast again.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] This decision was overturned on appeal by the High Court in *ABC v Lenah Game Meats Pty Ltd*.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] The judgment confirmed that journalists can use material obtained illegally by others in the public interest.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] The case is frequently cited as a landmark decision.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] In February 2012 Animal Liberation gained footage shot undercover over six days at Hawkesbury Valley Abattoir, depicting animals having their throats slit without being properly stunned, and pigs pummelled in the head with an iron bar.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] The footage was passed onto authorities, resulting in the New South Wales Food Authority closing the abattoir.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] Later the same year in August an investigation conducted over three months at Wally's Piggery at Murrumbateman captured footage of illegal animal husbandry practices, and back-room slaughter at a facility that was not an authorised slaughterhouse.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] Animal cruelty charges were laid following a raid as a result of the footage, but all charges were subsequently dropped in 2014.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] In June 2012 Campaign Director Emma Hurst released footage from an investigation into duck farming sheds from so-called free range duck meat producers.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] The footage showed ducks confined indoors without access to sunlight or ground water.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] This investigation formed the basis of complaints to the Australian Competition & Consumer Commission against two large duck producers.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] In December 2012, the Federal Court ordered Pepe's Ducks to pay $400,000 for false, misleading and deceptive conduct.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] Luv-a-Duck was ordered to pay $360,000 for misleading claims.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] In 2013 Animal Liberation received 140 hours of footage taken at an Inghams turkey processing plant in Tahmoor over a two-week period.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] The videos contained scenes of turkeys being bashed, kicked and stomped on.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] The footage sparked a renewed call from Animal Liberation for mandatory CCTV monitoring in all Australian abattoirs.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] Current chief executive officer Lynda Stoner was previously known for several roles on Australian television in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] Stoner had leading regular roles in the soap opera *The Young Doctors* from 1977 to 1979 and followed this with the police drama *Cop Shop*.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] In 1985 she played the glamorous villain Eve Wilder in the cult soap opera *Prisoner* and her character was spectacularly lynched during the infamous episode 600 riot, screened in 1986.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] This was followed by a guest role in the raunchy drama serial *Chances* in 1991 where she played a sex therapist.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] Stoner became a prominent spokesperson for animal rights issues in the early 1980s and subsequently left acting to focus on this area.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] Mark Pearson MLC formerly served as Executive Director of Animal Liberation.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] His main focus was on farm animals, particularly factory farming.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] Pearson was involved in advocating for the abolition of mulesing in sheep and convincing the Russian Federation to ban imports of kangaroo meat by exposing cruelty and hygiene problems.
[src:animal-liberation-organisation/animal-liberation-organisation] He has been a Member of the New South Wales Legislative Council since 2015, representing the Animal Justice Party, giving the party its first parliamentary representation.
